 goal, he slows down, proceeding with even greater caution, which is not surprising considering where he is going. Just ahead, a campfire glows, and around it, a press of enormous bodies. This is the home of the ogres, and wood elves are not welcome here. Yet he moves closer, and then stops, grasps a low-hanging tree branch, and pulls himself up, silently. Then, perched in the dark foliage of the tree, he listens.<br>
<br>
&quot;You call yourselves worshippers of Rallos Zek? The terrible God of War? And what do you do? You skulk in the bushes while others tread on your own lands! Your once-mighty empire, conquered by who? The elves, with their terrible magics? The humans, breeding like rabbits? No, I tell you! The dwarves are on your lands! The puny, short, stout drunkards with kettles on their heads! You have been forced to flee by these misfits, these midgets! Fie upon you!&quot; At the centre of the ogre circle, an imposing dark elf stands. Almost as tall as an ogre, he is dressed in armour as black as the night itself. The light from the fire is completely absorbed by the unholy metal, and only his face shows, blue-skinned, crowned by a veritable mane of black hair. After speaking, he folds his arms and gazes insolently, almost challengingly, at the ogres in front of him. A murmur goes through the crowd, but no one comes forward to speak. <br>
<br>
&quot;You have named your city Oggok! Revenge, you say? I tell you, the time for revenge is now! The planes have been opened, even unto the domain of the god Rallos Zek! March on Kaladim! Kill these pitiful midgets and bring glory to his name, and he will come down among you! This is the end of the Age, and war shall spring up in all the lands of Norrath. Oggok! Arise and fight!&quot; The ogres, perhaps not realizing what they had just agreed to, began to cheer, waving their enormous swords and spears above their heads. Then, one by one, they began to chant. Perhaps a chant from long ago, the shamans began it, slowly and powerfully. <br>
<br>
&quot;Oggok! Oggok! Oggok is ours! We were driven from our homes! We shall return, the dwarves will pay! Oggok! Oggok! Oggok!&quot;<br>
<br>
The chant grew louder and faster, as ogres began shouting and clashing their swords together in their frenzy. <br>
<br>
&quot;Oggok! Oggok! Oggok is ours! We were driven from our homes! We shall return, the dwarves will pay! Oggok! Oggok! Oggok!&quot;<br>
<br>
Drums began to beat and ogre shouts echoed throughout the forest. When it seemed it could get no louder, the words of the chant changed.<br>
<br>
&quot;War! War! Ogres of war! We march on Kaladim! Dwarves will die, dwarves will die! Oggok! Arise!&quot; <br>
<br>
With that, the ogres dispersed, running frantically to their homes for their armour and weapons, and shouting to all their friends. The ogres were going to war. Beside the campfire, the dark elf lowered his arms, as if to relax, then suddenly, in one motion, he threw a dagger into the tree ahead of him. The ranger had no time to move as the dagger flew straight at him, slicing deeply into his left arm. Blood spurted out of the wound, but he had no time to waste. Leaping from the tree, he gestured in the air, tracing out the lines of a spell. Instants later, a wolf was running through the forest, blood streaking from its left leg. There was a book, sitting innocently on a wooden pedestal in the forest, remarkably undisturbed for its location. The wolf ran up to it, placed its right paw on the open pages, and vanished. The calm night of the Feerott returned, and all was deathly silence.<br>
